            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Shannon Doyle\u2019s environmentalism was born in the damp, mossy forests of the Oregon coast. Raised by a high school biology teacher and a carpenter, her childhood was a masterclass in appreciating natural systems and skilled handiwork. She spent her youth cataloging tide pool creatures and watching her father reclaim old-growth timber, learning early that human impact could be either destructive or regenerative. This duality shaped her worldview and set her on a path of pragmatic idealism.\n\nHer educational journey took her to UC Santa Barbara for her undergraduate degree and then to Duke University for a graduate program in Environmental Management. Initially drawn to non-profit advocacy, Shannon grew frustrated with the slow pace of change. She realized the biggest impact could be made from within the system she sought to reform. This led her to sustainability consulting, a career where she could leverage corporate resources for environmental good. After a decade of climbing the ladder at a firm in Seattle, a director-level opportunity in San Francisco offered the influence she craved.\n\nNow 41, Shannon has carved out a successful and demanding life. A key turning point was the end of a long-term relationship in her mid-thirties, an amicable split over differing life priorities that solidified her focus on her career. She lives in a minimalist one-bedroom apartment in Hayes Valley, a neighborhood she loves for its walkability and central location. Her days begin with a run through the Panhandle and end with strategic planning for clients ranging from tech giants to apparel companies. Her 3.7-mile MUNI ride to her Financial District office is a non-negotiable part of her routine, a small daily practice of her core beliefs.\n\nHer social circle is small and tight-knit, consisting of other driven professionals who share her passion for hiking, farmers' markets, and sharp intellectual debate. While proud of her work\u2014helping corporations reduce their carbon footprint is no small feat\u2014Shannon dreams of a more tangible legacy. Her ultimate aspiration is to buy a plot of land in Sonoma or Mendocino County and establish a small-scale, sustainable vineyard and educational retreat, a place where she can finally close the loop between the corporate world she navigates and the Oregon soil she came from."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe was ten, sitting on a sawdust-covered stool in her father\u2019s workshop. He was planing a massive beam salvaged from a demolished cannery, the scent of cedar and salt air filling the space. He ran his hand over the smooth, revived wood and told her, \u201cNothing is ever truly lost, Shan. Just waiting for a new purpose.\u201d That quiet moment of transformation became her life\u2019s operating principle: things could be remade, systems could be healed. It was the seed of all her future work.\n\n***\n\n2.\nAt 26, she sat in a stuffy non-profit boardroom, listening to endless debate over a tiny budget for a river cleanup. A wave of suffocating futility washed over her. These were good people, but they were nibbling at the edges of a problem created by giants. A cold resolve settled in her chest: she wouldn't fight the system from the outside with petitions. She would learn its language, walk its halls, and change it from within. It was the day her idealism put on a suit.\n\n***\n\n3.\nIt was on their Seattle apartment balcony, tea growing cold in their mugs. They weren't fighting. Mark was tracing the floorplan of a suburban house, talking about school districts. Shannon saw her own future reflected in his eyes, and it wasn\u2019t hers. The sadness of the end was sharp, but beneath it was the clean, quiet hum of certainty. At 35, she chose the blueprint of her own life over one they couldn\u2019t share. The grief was real, but so was the freedom.\n\n***\n\n4.\nShe was 39, riding the Caltrain south for a client meeting. Glancing out the window, she saw it: the vast rooftop solar array glittering on the tech campus she\u2019d spent a year advising. It wasn't a pristine forest, but it was thousands of tons of carbon that wouldn't enter the atmosphere. A quiet, fierce pride bloomed in her chest. This was the impact she\u2019d chased from that stuffy boardroom years ago. This was why she came to San Francisco. It was pragmatic, corporate, and beautiful.\n\n***\n\n5.\nLast spring, at the Ferry Plaza Farmers' Market, she stood talking to a winemaker from Mendocino. The woman\u2019s hands were stained from her work, her face weathered by the sun. As she described the challenges of dry-farming, Shannon felt a visceral pull\u2014a longing for soil, for a legacy she could touch. In that moment, her high-rise office and the woman\u2019s dusty vineyard weren\u2019t separate worlds, but two ends of a journey she was determined to complete."
